It really depends on the type of covid patient. The most devices you're referring to are probably tracheal ventilators that typically require sedation. These are only used in hospitals and were the go-to treatment option early on in the pandemic. It actually causes a bunch of other complications so right now it's not the recommended initial treatment option. There are milder ventilation options called non-invasive ventilation that are masks that sit over your face similar to what some people use for sleep apnea (snoring). These can be used in a home setting and without sedation. Also they are cheaper but still run over 5,000 and up to 15,000 depending on type.

The solutions we're talking about are for milder covid cases for patients who need supplemental oxygen. Oxygen tanks are the cheapest option but require infrastructure to refill (either onsite at hospitals) or offsite in industrial locations. I'm not familiar with infrastructure in India, but in the US most hospitals have oxygen generation facilities to provide oxygen directly to hospital rooms and for refilling. The other main option would be some type of concentrator. Concentrators function by removing nitrogen from the air to provide 90%+ oxygen vs ~20% in the air. There are both stationary concentrators (bigger, provide better flow and plug into walls) and portable concentrators (mobile, can run on battery, less efficient). These units will run anywhere from 400 - 2000 depending on model. Flow is measured by L / min and on the high end will be 10L and on low end 2L.
*I am not a doctor but have had family members with COPD and invest in the space
One other consideration is that concentrators in general operate worse in humid environments, which I imagine India is. But we're probably less concerned about long term longevity for units anyways

Using multisig for this is really good. Multisig stands for multi-signature, it allows two or more users to sign a transaction as a group. There's an address that receives the funds which require multiple users to authorize transaction, rather than the single signature from that address.

Jeremie creates the donation address, adds signers (users) to the address, then sets the policy on the minimum of users it requires for transactions to happen. It's not only a form to divide the responsibility for possession of the funds but also to guarantee that the funds won't be lost because there will always exist people to approve (sign) transactions. Another great usecase to use our own address to receive the donations instead of everyone individually donating directly to the charity is that it will be easier to verify the donations and to claim it. When we receive a donation on our address will be sure what it is and from where it comes, then we send it all in a single payment which will be easier for us to pinpoint on the ledger.
For example, Jeremie adds 15 signers and makes a policy for 10 of 15. This means that if we gather 10 signers (users) we can still use the funds even if Jeremie is not around.
